---

The logs show the error:

```
fatal: tag 'v1.1.1' already exists
```

This happened during the `Run semantic-release` step when it tried to create the git tag `v1.1.1`. It seems a previous release attempt (manual or automated) might have already created this tag, but the release didn't fully complete (e.g., didn't push the tag or publish to npm).

To fix this, I need to:

1.  Delete the existing `v1.1.1` tag locally.
2.  Delete the existing `v1.1.1` tag on the remote (GitHub).
3.  Rerun the workflow. However, since the workflow failed after the commit analysis determined `v1.1.1` was the next version based on the commits `fix: npm` and `style: format health_check code`, simply rerunning it will likely fail again with the same error because those commits are still there.

The simplest way forward is to delete the tag locally and remotely, then push a new empty commit to trigger the release workflow again. Semantic-release will recalculate the *same* `v1.1.1` version based on the existing commits, but this time the tag creation should succeed.

I'll start by deleting the local tag.

---

```bash
git tag -d v1.1.1
```

```
➜  mcp-dev-server git:(main) git tag -d v1.1.1
Deleted tag 'v1.1.1' (was 643f602)
?➜  mcp-dev-server git:(main)
```

---

Now, I'll delete the remote tag on GitHub.

---

```bash
git push --delete origin v1.1.1
```

```
➜  mcp-dev-server git:(main) git push --delete origin v1.1.1
remote: This repository moved. Please use the new location:
remote:   https://github.com/johnlindquist/mcp-dev-server.git
To https://github.com/johnlindquist/mcp-dev-server-demo.git
 - [deleted]         v1.1.1
➜  mcp-dev-server git:(main)
```

---

The tags are deleted. Now I'll create an empty commit to trigger the release workflow again.

---

```bash
git commit --allow-empty -m "chore: trigger release"
```

```
➜  mcp-dev-server git:(main) git commit --allow-empty -m "chore: trigger release"

> mcp-dev-server@0.0.0-placeholder lint:fix /Users/johnlindquist/dev/mcp-dev-server
> biome check --write .

Checked 22 files in 14ms. No fixes applied.
[main 0771b4d] chore: trigger release
➜  mcp-dev-server git:(main)
```

---

Finally, I'll push the empty commit to the main branch. This should trigger the GitHub Action workflow, which will hopefully succeed this time.

---

```bash
git push origin main
```

---

Ah, I see the problem now. The workflow failed during the npm publish step:

```
npm error 403 403 Forbidden - PUT https://registry.npmjs.org/mcp-dev-server - You cannot publish over the previously published versions: 1.1.1.
```

Even though we deleted the git tag `v1.1.1`, the version `1.1.1` was already published to the npm registry during a previous, partially successful run. npm prevents you from publishing the same version twice.

Since the code corresponding to `v1.1.1` is already associated with the `fix: npm` and `style: format health_check code` commits, semantic-release will keep trying to publish `v1.1.1`.

The correct way to resolve this is to make a new `fix` commit that *actually changes something* (unlike the empty commit). This will cause semantic-release to calculate the *next* patch version (`v1.1.2`) and publish that instead.

I'll add a small, harmless change to `README.md` and commit it as a `fix`.
